The Prague Stock Exchange is down by the end of trading
The Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses after the crash this morning.
Transactions with shares of the Czech Energy Company (<0xC4><0x8C>EZ) amounted to nearly half of the usual daily trading volume.
The Prague stock exchange continued its slump on Monday from the start of trading on Tuesday, when it fell by almost six percent.
This time, Wall Street shares are falling.
This is also the reaction of the market to the outcome of the vote in the US House of Representatives, which refused to support the stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Fall of shares in Asia
Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall in stocks on Tuesday, though some of the losses over the course of the day were eventually cancelled.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng stock market index posted almost four percent during trading, but later wiped out some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which monitors Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, while the markets in Shanghai were closed.
The Sydney stock market lost more than five percent, but losses eventually dropped to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan stock market fell 3.6 percent, according to the index.
"The timing of the US rescue operation is uncertain and will affect the world's financial markets," said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Financial Council.
Hong Kong, although part of China, sets its monetary policy independently, that is, independently of the Chinese central bank.
In Hong Kong, interest rates are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said U.S. lawmakers should immediately restart talks and accept the financial system’s proposed bailout.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will also feel the consequences.
The Bloodbath of U.S. Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to subsidize the financial system that would have cost $700 billion (almost 12 trillion kroner).
Legislators have thus ignored President George Bush’s call for support for the plan.
Bush said the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks went through a bloodbath and the leading stock indexes recorded the biggest fall in 20 years.
The Dow Jones had a nearly seven percent drop, the last time it experienced a similar fall was in 1987.
The index fell before the vote, but as soon as it turned out that the proposal was not adopted in the House of Representatives, the index began to fall free.
Congress: U.S. could pump $700 billion into banks
The top leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush agreed on a broader form of the agreement and financial assistance to the U.S. financial system.
This will be voted on early next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in negotiations to approve the rescue plan in the form of $700 billion (about 12 trillion kroner) in financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
But there is no victory yet.
Congress needs to finalize some of the details of the agreement before they can release the final form of the law and their vote.
The financial support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the Financial Services Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
Senate sources say the bill will likely be voted on Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, there should be an announcement that the rescue plan will be approved, which is the first important psychological factor in the revival of financial markets.
However, due to the complexity of the mechanisms, there will be a "cooling-off" afterwards.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have taken a big step.
We have resolved our differences of opinion on what the form of the market stabilisation package should be,” said Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat.
The final vote could take place on Sunday.
Lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Saturday night to give the final form to the U.S. government fund.
This would have to buy up unsellable mortgages from financial companies, which would put financial companies at serious losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
“We are close to reaching a final agreement on a project that will work and that must be effective in the market at the same time.
The corrective action plan still needs to be continued, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
Signal to Asian Trading
The global financial crisis is having a major impact on stock markets, which are falling sharply.
Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid said lawmakers would seek a final settlement in Congress on Sunday.
This is to reassure investors before they start trading in Asian financial markets, where the time zone could be the first for Congress to influence Monday’s trade.
However, it is not clear when the two chambers of Congress will vote on the bill, nor whether the trial will be held at the last minute because of a problem.
Lawmakers hope the bill will be approved in the coming days.
However, the law is still going through a number of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the system shall be divided into two parts.
As President George Bush requested, the first $350 billion should be available as soon as possible.
However, Congress could block the release of the remaining amount, which was set at an additional $100 billion and later at $350 billion, if it gets the feeling that the program is not fulfilling its function.
President Bush has made progress in the negotiations.
Although the President may veto this resolution, Congress may overrule its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program remained, which was to acquire material assets for the purchase of bad mortgage securities that lost their value, since hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgage loans.
“We’ve worked everything out.
The House should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate should be able to vote on Monday,” said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
U.S. President Bush is also pleased with the progress made in the negotiations.
Bush spokeswoman Tony Fratto said the president was pleased with Saturday's progress and appreciated "bipartisan efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Restrictions on severance pay
The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, Christopher Dodd, said the legislators had agreed on responsibility for the financial program, protection of taxpayers from losses, termination of benefits, and timing of the funding plan.
The new law also restricts the so-called “busy” severance payments of directors participating in the program, and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
The fund should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We’ve worked very hard on this, and we’ve made great strides toward an agreement that will work and that will benefit all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes assistance for homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new installments for the mortgages it buys, with the aim of reducing the monthly installments of debtors and allowing them to keep their houses.
Marek: Spiritual Aid
David Marek, chief economist at Patria Finance, says the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
“This is because there is no way of knowing with what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be acquired.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government share losses,” Marek told iHNed.cz.
According to Marek, it is not so important whether the plan will be approved now or at the beginning of next week.
“It is more important that Congress decide this week whether to support the plan and give its blessing as soon as possible.
The spiritual significance of reaching an agreement that the plan will be approved is the most important thing at the moment," Marek said.
Duel on the edge: MP3 players vs. mobiles.
We will help you choose
While almost all mobile phones can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
It’s better to just buy a phone.
There are many reasons to buy an MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the needs of the future owner.
It’s probably hard to get a high-end expensive turntable at home to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc record.
On the one hand, such musical products do not appear on vinyl records, but from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this either.
However, if your shelves are full of art rock, jazz or blues vinyl records, then you probably dream of such a turntable.
This is similar to traveling, or compressed - simplified to MP3 music.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to give 8,000 kroner for a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan will probably find it difficult to accept a 20-kroner market earphone.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
There's a wide choice.
Battery life also matters
Some high-end music players can do much more than simply play music, but also do what most mobiles don’t even accidentally do.
No other device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions of calling and texting, you can play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera, and even navigate.
And if you consider smartphones and communicators, you will also have a small computer in your pocket.
This is a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no television can take photos.
However, multi-functional mobiles also have their drawbacks.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the more the display sends you to the charger.
And music playback is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile devices can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
With cheap mobiles, you should be aware that they won’t play for you for more than a few hours.
If you’re also making phone calls here and there, get an extra charger for your workplace just in case – this also applies to more expensive devices.
You won’t have this problem with MP3 players, even the worst ones can last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
The following issue occurs when uploading music to mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and besides, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but few card readers can cope without an adapter with the miniature memory cards used in mobile phones.
With a few exceptions (iPod), you don’t need any special software.
It is enough to charge the device from the computer with music via USB.
The majority of mobile phones and players create their own music library, sorted by artist, album, genre, or user rating.
Some devices only show a tree structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some know both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobiles know more
When choosing a specific device, first of all, ask about the battery life, memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output, and, of course, the convenience of operation.
If music is primarily your background and you only listen to it for a short time each day, for example on the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 will suit you.
This is something that any mobile phone can do.
You don’t even have to pay special attention to what music formats your mobile or player can.
With MP3, they all cope, and the vast majority of the music that reaches you will be in just that format.
MP3 is one of the most popular formats, and the vast majority of devices can also handle music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and your iPod) is less common.
Better mobiles also allow you to buy music online, for example.
It is enough to visit the respective pages of the provider (or other provider) through the mobile Internet and purchase the song or album.
This service in itself can be a powerful argument for purchasing a music mobile.
Unfortunately, service providers are limited to lousy and usually only annual radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (whether via GSM, the internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people keep their mobile devices with them at all times.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you’ll be scanning your phone in your pocket while the forgotten MP3 player is lying at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry your headphones or at least your hands-free devices.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker that almost all mobile, but only a few MP3 players have.
For many, the biggest advantage of music mobiles will probably be the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3000 kroner.
Between three and four thousand kroner you can get enough decent walkman.
However, for the most part, you are limited by the lack of output from conventional headsets.
The best and most technically equipped phones with traditional 3.5 mm hole earphones can cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players, however, is that they are easy to use.
The simplest - by no means necessarily the cheapest players (see our selection) really everyone can cope with.
A minimal function, a handling similar to that of a conventional cassette player or gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of a crash in the form of an accidentally switched on mobile internet, and no risk of a huge bill for data transmission.
Which device to choose
The cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have slots for removable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
If you buy the right card, it can cost up to 2,000 kroner.
But be careful.
Basic types only support cards with a maximum capacity of up to 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones know what to do with up to 8 GB of memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and even want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or irivert.
Based on the capacity (up to 2 GB) you do not need to spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you belong to more demanding students, choose more specialized mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsungs).
These devices also have a separate MP3 control button, so the convenience of operation is closer to the MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson is the farthest away in the industry, with its Walkman series of mobile phones having the same user interface as the MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players of the above-mentioned brands can offer the same service in the same price range up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will arrive in the Czech Republic later this year.
Maybe.
The Czech mobile market is relatively developed and our service providers offer virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
Nevertheless, something is missing here for us – a virtual service provider that forces classic service providers to make substantial price reductions.
Maybe it won't be for much longer.
On the Mobil.cz website we have written many times that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which pointed out that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in other EU countries.
Following the European Commission's latest move to regulate roaming charges, this may lead to a controversial situation - for some Czech mobile operators, text messages sent from abroad will be cheaper than those sent domestically.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple: there is no real competition.
This may sound counterintuitive, as we have three mobile networks and our penetration is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office, often agrees with this, as he has previously stated on several occasions that there is no room for a new service provider in the Czech Republic.
Perhaps it is true that the classic provider with its own network probably doesn’t have much of a chance anymore (however, it would probably have a hard time finding a frequency).
But there is another option - the virtual service provider.
It was the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market that led to a significant price drop, to which the classic service providers had to react.
In the meantime, even before big fish like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market in Great Britain, voices like ours were heard.
However, it has been proven that such providers have their place and can be truly successful.
However, for example, we do not have to go too far.
In February of this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual service provider Mobilking in Poland.
In less than six months, this service provider managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider there.
Meanwhile, behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
Virtual service providers have the advantage of being able to focus on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate efficiently, you need far fewer customers than a traditional service provider.
It does not entail relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers in the world thus tend to appear as low-cost – offering cheap calls and sms, which, however, are often offset by fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers text messages that are at least 50% cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it’s a pretty good move to bet on a target group.
This service is specifically focused on men.
“Real men choose Mobilking — who they like, who they can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobil Entertainment Company, the virtual service provider.
It is difficult to say whether an idea similar to that in Poland can work in Hungary.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>, Vodafone’s spokesman, doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfactory in terms of the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not seem to be promising.
Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, said in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
This indirectly demonstrated that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not very sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything in their power to avoid any potential competition.
The GTS Novera Group has not been hiding its interest in launching a virtual service provider for some time now, which wants to take another step towards making Telefonica O2 a true competitor in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in providing not only fixed line but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations,” says Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
There may be better times ahead.
From unofficial information, it seems that we can be lucky with the first virtual service provider already by the end of the year.
His birth, however, is surrounded by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At this point in time, we don’t think there is any place for a fully-fledged virtual service provider in the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very special.
So far, we have not been approached by a single subject offering a complex and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, from Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica 02, told Mobil.cz.
The special situation of the Czech market is also referred to by other operators.
Martina Kemrová, T-Mobile’s spokesperson, said: “We have not yet recorded a single viable and bilaterally beneficial business project on which to base further.”
And he added: “In the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it is unlikely that any virtual service providers will show up.
We should have a concrete agreement on the table right now to be able to think in the short term."
Vodafone is turning its attention to meeting its own 3G licensing requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to discussions with potential virtual service providers, particularly in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we consider to be the most profitable for our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find partners to build shared networks for high-speed mobile internet.”
Responsible agencies - one on one with service providers
The procedure of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of a new operator would mean an increase in competition, a decrease in prices and, consequently, a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier to enter such a competition?
When service providers have something important, they are able to cooperate, as evidenced by the tug-of-war around the birth of U:fon.
<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was probably under the greatest pressure around the birth of T-Mobile’s U:fon.
The publicly available information on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> website attests to this.
But right now, U:fon is a good argument for why we should not allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrová added: "The competitive environment in the mobile market has recently been amplified by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of a new player to the market and its services would be highly demanding."
However, in view of this attitude of the mobile operators, the complete lack of interest of the Czech regulators is downright astonishing.
In the meantime, it is not just the attitude of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which, unfortunately, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, has no right to interfere in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
Only the Competition Authority is entitled to do so.
But the office is characteristically related to the whole problem.
“The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market would only be possible after the agreement between the mobile operator and the virtual operator on the leasing of the necessary infrastructure has been concluded.
So far, no such contracts have been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not of sufficient interest to traditional service providers," Kristián Chlapua from the External Relations Department of the Hungarian Competition Authority (GVH) said in reply to our question.
A statement like this from the representatives of the service providers would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from an office that should represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensure that no one can abuse their market position, this is more than strange.
Especially if Kristián Chalupa adds: "In countries where virtual service providers usually operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the price of mobile services."
However, it is probably not in the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to exert pressure on the market environment to function properly and to reduce prices.
In this case, it is truly shocking that the reaction of the three mobile operators reveals a quite touching harmony.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is almost self-evident.
As in the case of filling stations, the exact same petrol prices are probably only the result of chance and tough competition.
“The Office has not detected any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the service providers has a leading position, i.e. they do not have a proportionately greater responsibility for their market activities.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market for virtual service providers are also likely to be lacking for the telecom regulator," Chalupa said.
The presentation of the market leadership is one of the many points of dispute.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, no Czech operator is in a leading position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different approach - the creation of a virtual service provider always requires approval from the network operator.
And the mobile operator, relatively logically, has a monopoly on its own network.
So, in a certain segment, it is necessarily dominant.
But even if we did not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning to UOHS that three mobile operators are strikingly similar.
In the meantime, complaints from a range of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in the course of negotiations with all service providers.
Transferring responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS takes its hands off the whole case.
We have seen this in some similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted law on telecommunications, the extension of the powers of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the field of economic competition in telecommunications has not been implemented, although many experts hoped that the situation would improve.
Representatives of the UOHS should know this well, but they probably have different interests.
It works when no one is watching.
Meanwhile, the operation of some kind of pseudo-virtual service providers, many of which are already operating in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own mobile phone service price lists, which, however, are only partially public.
These are multi-level marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the selected ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic corporate client against the service provider, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a featured customer, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such advance purchases.
"If there were cases that he talks about, it would be a breach of contract that we would deal with and that could lead to the termination of cooperation with that company," said Martina Kemrová in response to our question on this issue.
But it is unlikely that news of such activity has not reached the responsible people of the mobile operators.
In particular, the three companies mentioned above may have thousands of customers.
In the meantime, no service provider is defending itself against such a procedure.
These companies have not negligible profits from their activities and, unlike real virtual service providers, they are not particularly threatened with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns of potential problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have it in its entirety as the general customers of mobile operators."
But that's exactly what <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> should be saying.
In addition, there is another question that arises for the UOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why are they blocking the birth of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the UOHS has a relatively strong authority to expose such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the service providers that they did not suspect anything of this kind and that their commercial conditions prohibit this.
When We're Not the Most Expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a noticeable decrease in the price of services.
Meanwhile, in virtually all the countries where virtual service providers were established, the classic service providers tried to prevent their establishment to a greater or lesser extent.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied with the market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, in the developed countries, it was precisely at these moments that regulators intervened, in no way protecting the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Then, either through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual service provider, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are passing the whole thing on to each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competences are useful for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is really coming soon, the Czech mobile market may be in motion again.
If a service provider were to allow the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it would be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the refusal (discrimination) of additional interested parties.
And compared to the rest of Europe, perhaps we won’t be making more expensive calls.
