Sleepless Nights for Hypo Real Estate Creditors
The German banking system is relatively stable, federal finance minister Peer Steinbr<0xC3><0xBC>ck said just last week.
It is fortunate that the politician used the word “relatively” and even weaved into his message that the German banking sector is not spared by crisis-like developments.
Because it happened this weekend.
Daxon-listed Munich-based real estate company Hypo Real Estate (HRE) has received a multi-billion dollar loan from a consortium of German banks to protect itself from market turbulence.
A source familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that the loan subsidies amounted to 35 billion euros.
Hypo Real Estate only has to pay interest on the part used.
The money comes partly from private banks and partly from public banks.
In the background are the losses of the Depfa subsidiary.
According to a newspaper report, Depfa, a state-funded company, lent money for long-term projects and refinanced itself for them on an extremely short term - which is no longer possible because of the distrust in the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank’s cash reserves decreased by 95 percent to EUR 2.37 million, and its equity ratio also declined moderately, from 1.6 percent to 1.45 percent.
Current income and net cash income decreased to zero compared to the same period last year, and income from receivables and certain securities and the liquidation of credit provisions declined by more than 70 percent to EUR 5 million.
Only thanks to higher revenues from the reimbursement of the ex-post settlement costs of the conversion of the former Depfa group, as well as the reimbursement of interest according to the Decree on duties and the business brought to the companies belonging to the group, the income deficit of around 16% was relatively moderate.
The former state financier, after its privatisation in 1990, first speculated on corporate real estate loans, which were later segregated in Aeral Bank.
Due to the lack of classical public funding, Depfa has become more involved in infrastructure projects and private-public-partnership (PPP) projects with private investors and the state, and has expanded its activities internationally.
For the value of the subsidiaries, Hypo Real Estate must now make descriptions that have a "significant impact" on the group's profit and loss statement, they said fairly generally.
In fact, no dividend was paid.
Dividends were reduced to a third by 2007.
Since taking over Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has become a major state and infrastructure financier.
Compared to other financial institutions, it is more dependent on interbank market refinancing, since it has no customer deposits.
With the collapse of the American investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, lending between banks has stalled as banks guard their liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs short-term assets every year to refinance part of Depfa’s loan portfolio – some €50 billion.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group’s financing needs are covered for the foreseeable future and the company is protected from “the influence of the currently largely dysfunctional international financial markets.”
According to other sources, thanks to the money, the refinancing is ensured until the end of 2009.
On the other hand, Georg Funke, Chairman of the Board of Directors of HRE, stated that the Hypo Real Estate group does not have to use the financial markets for a foreseeable period of time.
The Federal Bank of Germany and the Federal Financial Services Supervisory Authority (BaFin) believe that the marketability of the Hypo Real Estate group is now assured.
This gives hope to the bank’s shareholders and creditors.
But because of the dynamics and immensity of the crisis, they cannot be sure.
It is not even inconceivable that funding should not be fully used.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out.
According to the late-night news on Saturday, the bank was still on the verge of bankruptcy, but even its temporary rescue could not calm the mood.
The share price fell by 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
In contrast, bond prices hold up fairly well.
While the first-ranking debt has barely changed, the price of subordinated bonds has fallen significantly.
The crisis particularly affected the bonds of the former subsidiary W<0xC3><0xBC>rttemberg Hypo and, understandably, the maturities beyond 2009.
While Hypo Real Estate bonds used to seem like a speculative investment alternative, their value stability must now be seen as dependent on the stability of the international financial system in the wake of the escalating banking crisis and the fact that the financial institution took over Depfa and brought the crisis almost to the house.
As long as central banks, governments and less vulnerable business banks are still ready to support the system, it is possible to start by repaying the annuities on time.
Or it will be something that almost no one dares to hope for at the moment, that the financial crisis will be overcome in the next 15 months.
However, the reports of partial nationalisation have reduced the probability of certainty to a justifiable hope.
For long-term lenders, sleepless nights can be caused by the decision to divest from their investment.
However, short-term investors can use the sale as a reserve for taxes on exchange gains in the years to come.
