Rats have emotions, too.
A rat or a moth escapes in case of danger. Does this mean that you feel fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux believes that animals have emotions.
But how can we test whether they feel the same when they act like us?
For years, famous scientists have published their articles in the Internet magazine "Edge".
SPIEGEL ONLINE looks at the answers to the question "What do you think is real without being able to prove it?" in one of its series.
I believe that animals have emotions and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it, but it's true that we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that the basic configuration of all human brains is the same.
However, as we look at other species and explore issues of perception, or consciousness in general, we arrive at difficult terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: pretend to be dead, run or attack.
Humans behave in a similar way, from which some researchers infer comparable subjective experiences.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experiences to animals.
Circuits related to human consciousness, on the one hand, almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and executive/control functions).
This vast area is more highly developed in man than in other primates, and appears to be completely absent in other organisms.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, such as knowing who we are or the ability to plan and make decisions, it is reasonable to assume that humans are even different from other primates.
Another dramatic feature lies in the linguistic nature of man: Since a significant part of human experience is connected with language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not dependent on language, it would certainly be influenced by language, so that animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
It is therefore difficult to determine what consciousness might be like in the case of other animals.
If consciousness cannot be measured as an internal and subjective thing, and cannot be analysed on the basis of our own experiences because of the special hardware, then its research presents us with serious problems.
Most of my discussions are about the content of conscious living, but there is another aspect of consciousness that is probably more accessible to science.
The consciousness processes of animals could be examined regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in experiments on the short-term memory of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
However, this assumption, which was also investigated by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, relies more on the neural connections of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: Both may or may not be the same.
Interestingly, this hypothesis also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the formation of visualization.
What does this mean for emotions?
This is because an emotional system, like that of fear, is activated in a brain that is aware of its own actions.
What we call “fear” is therefore the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defense system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) occupies a working memory.
In this way, emotions are closely linked to areas of the cerebral cortex that are characteristic of primates and especially humans.
In addition to the linguistic nature, perception is subdivided into subtle stages, because with the help of words and grammar, we are able to distinguish and categorize states in order to describe them not only to ourselves, but also to others.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, is of the opinion that emotions are derived from simpler activities of the cortex and body-sensing areas of the brain stem, as is Jaak Pankseep, who, however, prefers to focus on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it can easily play a role in cross-species emotions.
In theory, I can't deny it, but I think it's unprovable.
Pankseep believes that what appears to be fear in rats and humans is likely to be fear in both cases: How can we control whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in the same way?
When a cockroach escapes danger, does he feel fear?
In my opinion, just the same behavior is not proof of the same experience.
Although neural comparison helps, rats and humans have similar brains, but cockroaches have no brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for emotions?
And even if it could be proven in humans, how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, but maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have emotions.
However, I do not know how to prove this.
And because their emotions are suspected to be fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to study the emotional behavior of rats rather than their emotional emotions.
In any case, progress in this area is promising at the neural level, if we measure the same in rats and humans.
Just as in the case of rats, I do not search for language and consciousness, nor do I search for emotions, for I do not know whether they exist.
