Discussion on bilingual education: Continuous exposure to the English language environment
In this section of the Education Monitor, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss candidates’ views on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, an experienced researcher in California Studies and senior director of educational research at the Pacific Institute for Public Policy Research, is the co-author of the book “Not As Good As You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs School Choices.”
It is not easy to please voters from Spanish-speaking areas.
This includes Barack Obama’s proposals on education.
According to Obama’s campaign, “African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” and this is true.
To overcome such performance differences, Obama’s education plan explicitly advocates, among other things, “transitional bilingual education” for English learners.
At the same time, for Obama, the question is whether his commitment to bilingual education, with its emphasis on non-English language school education, outweighs his interest in overcoming the big performance gaps.
Take, for example, the Sixth Street Prep charter primary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
Most of the students in the school are Hispanic and low-income.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have recently arrived, are learning English.
Nevertheless, 100% of the fourth graders achieved an excellent result in the state mathematics exam in 2008.
Equally impressive is that 93% of fourth graders passed the English Language and Literature exam.
This incredible achievement was not achieved by the means that Obama would prefer.
Sixth Street places emphasis on repetition, practice, continuous assessment of skills, and rejection of excuses.
In addition, and this is what Obama should take into account, Sixth Street director Linda Mikels says, the school's educational principle is to "immerse" English-speaking students "fully" into the language environment.
The essence of the immersion method is the almost exclusive use of the English language in teaching other subjects.
Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, said: “We have had an overwhelming success in seeing that if someone walked into a classroom, they wouldn’t notice who the student was who had just arrived from Mexico 12 months earlier.”
"It works," he said, "it works for us."
Would Obama set schools such as Sixth Street Prep as an example to be followed by other schools that teach a significant number of Spanish-speaking and English-speaking students?
The results of the school should make the answer clear, but because of the education policy of his own party (National Education Associations have long supported bilingual education), and because he himself consistently stands for bilingual education, we cannot be sure of Obama’s reaction.
While he agrees that immigrants should learn English, Obama recently downplayed the issue when he said people shouldn’t worry so much about the “exclusive English” of the legislation.
Instead, he said, "they should make their children speak Spanish."
If Obama really wants to reduce the gap between results, he should seriously study the models that work, rather than look down on and ignore them.
The renewed concerns about the economy led to a sharp fall in oil prices
Oil prices fell sharply on Monday due to concerns that America’s rescue plan for the financial markets will not be able to revive the economy.
Crude oil stocks fell seven percent to $99.80 this morning on the New York Stock Exchange.
Prices have fallen by more than $20 a barrel since last Monday.
Over the past two weeks, commodity exchanges have been rocked by the Wall Street financial turmoil and some powerful hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After prices reached $145.29 per barrel in July, they fell to almost $90 per barrel at the beginning of this month, before falling again under the influence of the immense uncertainty of the financial markets.
On Monday, concerns again gripped investors, even after congressional leaders announced that they had reached an agreement over the weekend on an economic rescue operation, the largest in history.
The news has been overshadowed by concerns that the financial crisis will not end for a long time to come.
As the latest event in the unfolding crisis, Citigroup will acquire Wachovia Corporation’s banking business, the government announced on Monday.
In the meantime, the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg partially nationalized the European financial conglomerate Fortis.
Analysts at Barclays Capital said as a result of the desperate weekend talks, "it appears that the rescue operation has failed to revive the stock market's trading appetite."
As the economic situation worsens, it is expected that demand for commodities such as oil will also decline.
“The future of the equity, interest and foreign exchange markets around the world has become uncertain,” a Deutsche Bank analyst wrote to investors.
“We don’t think the ‘epidemic’ will be avoided in the commodities market either.
The biggest question from a commodity exchange perspective is to what extent the U.S. "disease" is infecting the entire world, especially China."
As the slowdown in economic growth led to a decline in oil consumption, bank analysts cut back on their expectations for next year, reducing their oil and gas price forecasts for 2009 by 20%.
