The well-rested Gebrselassie breaks its own world record
Ethiopian Haile Gebrselassie once again showed why many consider him to be the best middle and long distance runner who ever lived, when he broke his own world record in Berlin on Sunday, making him the first to run the 42.2 km in 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With a win on the comfortably flat track at 2:03:59, Gebrselassie improved his previous result of 2:04:26 by 27 seconds, which he had achieved in Berlin last year.
By the age of 35, Gebrselassie had set the 26th world record in her career in such a variety of fields that she had won the world championship or world record in almost every race from the 1500 metres to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic marathon, fearing that air pollution would exacerbate her asthmatic problems.
Instead, he entered the Berlin Marathon.
In almost perfect conditions – sunny weather, initially at 9 <0xC2><0xB0>C and finally at 13 <0xC2><0xB0>C – Gebrselassie won on Sunday at an incredible speed of 2 minutes and 56 seconds per kilometre.
Since runners such as Gebrselassie and Kenyan Paul Tergat, who had never run a marathon before, have turned to longer distances, the marathon record has fallen by more than two minutes in the past decade, since Brazil’s Ronaldo da Costa won in 1998 with a 2:06:05 finish in Berlin.
After Sunday’s victory, Gebrselassie told reporters that two weeks ago he had a cramp in his legs and was unable to work out for two weeks.
It is obvious that during the forced rest he was refreshed and not rusty.
"I'm so glad," Gebrselassie told reporters.
"Everything went perfectly.
I started training again a week ago, and today I had doubts, but in the end everything went well.”
He has received some criticism, particularly from Kenya, Ethiopia's rival in East Africa, for using too many assistive devices in his races, generally avoiding many world-renowned marathon runners, relying on his pace runners as if he were running on track, and putting world records ahead of the competition.
However, this criticism hardly diminishes Gebrselassie's greatness in long-distance running.
Gebrselassie reached the midpoint with four Kenyan runners at 1:02:04 on Sunday.
Two top Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, gave the rhythm to Gebrselassie after the speed runners were tired.
Not much more than 4,8 km before the finish, Gebrselassie overtook Kwambai with one last sprint, finishing second at 2:05:36, improving his individual best by 5 minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Kazakhstan-born Irina Mikitenko, who is now a German citizen, finished a remarkable year with her seventh fastest victory, 2:19:19.
The world record is set by British Paula Radcliffe at 2:15:25.
Last spring, the 36-year-old Mikitenko won the London Marathon with a surprise result of 2:24:14.
He was not allowed to participate in the Beijing Olympics due to his alleged back injury, but he recovered quickly and won the Berlin Marathon, where he improved his personal best by five minutes. This was the third marathon distance run he participated in.
He won the race with a clever calculation: first, he allowed a group of four Ethiopians and Kenyans to advance and gain significant leadership, and then after running about 30 km, he went after them.
Ethiopian Askale Tafa Magarsa finished second with a time of 2:21.31, while Kenyan Helena Kiprop finished third with a time of 2:25:01.
A Separate City, the Pride and Perplexities of Blacks
Located in Greater Orlando, a few miles from everything that glitters, sounds, and is huge, the theme park hides a quiet little town where the pride and complexities of the African-American experience of life are born.
Eatonville, the first purely black city to be integrated into the country and which was the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as it was described in 1935: "the five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guavas and two schools, without prison."
It's a place of pilgrimage now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have attended the annual Zora Festival, a series of celebrations held in honor of Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet, in many ways, the city he described and made a tourist attraction—which is also in the Florida guidebook published by the Federal Writers Project of the Depression—is separate from its surroundings.
As independent, dignified, and closed-minded as it was in the 1930s, Hurston wrote that black people in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with white people who “know so little about us that they don’t know what they’re missing.”
Even in the year when black presidential candidate Barack Obama calls for an open discussion on the race issue, many here distrust the gaze of outsiders.
“We’re very careful about how they tell our story,” said Hortense Jones, 59, who has lived here all her life and is a member of the city’s oldest church.
"You have to say it right."
Eatonville has long been characterized by the paradox of victory and struggle.
It is both a historic model of black engagement and a community of almost 2,400 people with poverty rates double the national average.
It is partly a literary node, and partly an example of a sometimes debased, sometimes lauded, southern, urban, black culture that flourishes in the shade of oak trees.
It’s no surprise that people here are proud and defensive at the same time.
The image of Eatonville has been important since Zora (here everyone calls Hurston).
In books written in honest, strong dialects, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937), he presented his hometown to the world.
The five paragraphs of the Florida guidebook transformed the city, which lies along Route 17. This road leads from the long-forgotten center of Florida to one of the sites of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was as brave as a drum roll in both life and literature, introduced his readers to the business of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then looked into the more intimate spheres.
To the right of the road is the modern public school, with a brown background with white borders, carefully maintained courtyards and playgrounds, tended by Howard Miller, though he can hardly read or write.
She mentioned the widow Dash’s new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn “sells all kinds of drinks and anything that might be needed in the transitional accommodations.”
Thus, in a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to autonomy, but also to illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
It is clear that Fodor's guidebook presented it differently.
This description was not liked by everyone.
"Zora told things the way they were," reported 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls. They were immortalized by Hurston by quoting from the skimpy songs that men sang about their beauty.
He added, "Some people didn't like that."
Hurston is still remembered here as the living eccentric who often visited his home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston stormed into town, he usually arrived unannounced in a roaring Chevrolet, smoking cigarettes, and wearing long pants, in a city where people are still proud of their dignified dress.
Most people were charmed, Franklin said, but many were foreboding it.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” Franklin said.
However, on the terrace overlooking Sabelia Lake, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added, swinging in his chair: "He never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books were not republished.
It seemed that Eatonville, along with most of the rest of the world, had forgotten about it.
Although once a popular writer, Langston is a contemporary of Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had lived before.
In Eatonville, there were no major commemorations or large public readings.
“I don’t think they understood how much he enriched the world, or what he left us,” said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston’s 2003 biography, Enveloped in the Rainbow.
The turning point came in 1980.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-lane road through the city instead of the two-lane main street, Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in the life of the community.
The expanding Orlando has already penetrated the interstate via Interstate 4 on the city's western border.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering after a difficult period of history.
Among other things, forced integration put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the struggles over racial mixing made the community taste the hate.
“At the time, a group of white boys came over and threw oranges and other things at people sitting on the side of the road,” Franklin said.
"There was a woman who died from this.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a letter to The Orlando Sentinel in 1955, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's decision on violent integration, saying that the decision, "Brown v. Board of Education, offends rather than respects my species."
Today, residents say that the desegregation of schools, while in some respects positive, has weakened the cohesion of the Egonville people and undermined young people’s self-confidence.
“Black kids are used to being hugged — I remember — by a man hugging his teacher in the morning and in the evening,” N.Y. Nathiri, Ella Dinkins’ daughter, executive director of the nonprofit Preserve the Eatonville Community, said in a statement.
“This lasted as long as students and teachers came from a common place,” he added.
“We didn’t hug our white teacher because he was a white teacher — I mean, there were cultural differences between us,” Nathiri said.
However, human rights have helped lift many other Zora Neale Hurstons—black writers, actors, and artists who have risen above prejudice as he did, with self-confidence and lines as optimistic as these: “How can anyone deprive himself of the enjoyment of my company?
This is incomprehensible to me.”
In 1975, Alice Walker made a pilgrimage to Hurston’s unmarked grave and began to struggle to restore her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway was placed on the shelves of bookstores, re-emerging him as one of America's role models.
The road project would have started just as Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the spotlight.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw him as a savior.
The community began organizing a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the county would ruin with its main road.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and since then, many have returned to the celebration every January.
Several years later, the county withdrew its road construction proposal.
“Because of the five-lane highway, the community has been revitalised and switched to full speed, which is a real civic pride,” Nathiri said.
Boyd said, "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the road construction project helped change the city’s image of itself.
More and more people were coming from outside the city, such as attorney Rachelle Munson, who started going to church in 1993, and the locals began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Historical Register in 1998.
In 2006, a new, one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) was opened on the re-enveloped and beautified Kennedy Avenue.
Eatonville remains Florida's cuckoo's egg: it's not exactly ten kilometers from downtown Orlando, but it sometimes feels like a suburban side street during summer rain; as small as when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today, 90% of the population is black.)
The outsiders, who come here looking for Eatonville’s story and message, are still treated with caution.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things—such as Eatonville’s oldest fresco, painted by a white man and depicting blacks working in the fields—should not be photographed.
In Eatonville, many, including the self-confident teacher Jones, who is particularly drawn to bright red, fear that their segregated community will be misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival became more and more widespread, the pride of the hometown also grew.
Young people, in particular, increasingly view Eatonville as Hurston saw his own race: wonderful, with its problems and everything, neither better nor worse, just as proud, creative, diligent, foolish and confused as other racial and ethnic groups in America.
There is a genuine civic attachment in the words of Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return after college to take a job with the local government or the police that he believes are in need of help.
And it seems younger people have learned to describe Eatonville correctly, like the 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon.
"Most people who just travel through here think this city is nothing compared to the rest," Alondra Kenon said recently after church service on Sunday.
“But if you stop and take some time to get to know its history, it’s a very beautiful city.”
Here in New York, we all speak the language of finance.
Nothing has changed on the surface.
If tourists didn’t mind the newsstands and huge TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn’t notice they were in the middle of a storm.
They would never realize that with glass-walled, beehive-shaped offices overhead, the bankers and hedge fund managers who control New York have been living through the most difficult days since 1929.
Couriers are still rolling their metal tea carts through the sidewalks, delivering trays of muffins for morning meetings.
Spanish-speaking men still shuffle between the blocks, carrying like a human mule fifty-something embroidered shirts that hang over their shoulders in a yoke-like loop.
Office workers are still waiting in line for their morning sweet pastries at the food trucks on the sidewalk, and it is still impossible to take a taxi on weekdays between 4 and 7 p.m.
I didn’t feel like there was any crisis until Thursday afternoon, despite all the ominous news, I decided to open a new bank account.
Although I had deliberately planned to settle the matter in the afternoon at the local branch of my JP Morgan Chase bank, I had about 20 people lined up in front of me.
Not at the cashier’s window, where you can withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service desk, where older customers order a checkbook, tourists ask for directions to Macy’s store, and where new customers open a bank account.
Many before me—I learned later from Starr, the banker “assigned to me”—were lined up with the same intention as I did.
However, unlike me, they have already withdrawn their money from smaller banks in their area of residence, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Staten Island.
They took money from so-called savings banks (which are like housing cooperatives), credit unions, and small-town savings banks that operate in only one state and supposedly treat their customers as family members.
Over the past year, 15 of these banks have gone silently bankrupt.
In recent days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in capital, has gone into receivership, and when New Yorkers left for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, was looking for a bank bailout with savings of $440 billion.
The office and shopkeepers in front of me, fearing another collapse, moved their money to a bank that seemed like a safe haven, the bank that makes the most capital injection buy-outs on Wall Street.
Over the past few weeks, ordinary New Yorkers have become experts in finance.
A woman at a local Chinese store spoke on her phone about the bankrupt Lehman Brothers bank and its giant-looking CEO, Dick Fuld, as if she were complaining about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed custodian of my apartment block in his fifties, changed the subject, and we weren't talking about Brad and Angelina or my food delivery like we used to.
He said to me after I went to the bank: "I have invested all my savings in money market instruments.
I've changed, I'm not taking any chances."
