A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were “deeply shaken” by the desecration, which took place shortly before the end of the Muslim religious month of Ramadan.
Meanwhile, Austria is conducting an examination of conscience following yesterday's parliamentary elections, during which the language of political balances has been tipped to the right.
The two far-right parties, which won almost 30% of the vote, campaigned for the Future of Austria, a strongly anti-immigration law, and some of their slogans were branded xenophobic by their critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, president of the Freedom Party, which received more than 18 percent of the vote, expressed his disapproval of the campaign against headscarves and burqas, as well as food allegedly associated with Islam.
At the party’s final meeting in Vienna, he spoke of a “European brotherhood” that would prevent the strengthening of Islam.
Both parties want to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of the ongoing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
