“I don’t take photos on stage because I want to introduce the artist from a personal point of view.” – G<0xC3><0xBC>nther Bauer
No set, no ruffles, no dancing shoes.
The grand masters of flamenco up close, without the excitement of the performance: to get to know the everyday faces of the dancers.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, ordinary people.
And these two sides cannot be separated, except in the intimate moments away from the audience, when we can gaze at a personal gesture, grasp the depth of a caught look, or marvel at the beauty of the inactive but expressive hand of the artist who is not about to perform on stage.
The German G<0xC3><0xBC>nther Bauer in his photo series Flamenco-people combines the theatricality of singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser-known everyday side of the masters.
Through the photographs, flamenco presents its specific iconography from different points of view.
The exhibition, which is part of the Flamenco Photography Month, "reflects the growing international significance of flamenco every day," the artist believes, adding that the flamenco-people "would be anyone's role, as the viewer realizes that these images do not represent artists in a typical way.
These street-shot people are artists who can bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and captivate the audience.
At the same time, stage photography is not suitable for capturing their personality.
Their personality and character reside in the very depths of their being.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to use the camera to capture the personalities of the greats of flamenco.”
Inspired by the Cante de las Minas festival, Bauer embarked on his long journey in 1997, using a record camera to create portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers.
These portraits are reminiscent of classical photography thanks to the camera and the choice of theme.
The use of various stylistic tools, however, breaks with traditional pictorial representation and suggests modernity. The following thought faithfully reflects Bauer's idea of flamenco: "This is a music with traditional roots, however, it changes from day to day and is always impressive."
It is not the dance, not the song or the music in itself, but rather the personality and character of the artist that charms the audience.
The main motif of the works on display in the El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata Gallery these days is the search for an encounter with the essence, the artistic sorcery, which becomes visible through the way of perception, existence and representation.
Famous flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are the hallmarks of this collection of photographs featuring almost sixty artists.
The project has also become a flamenco anthology, and an album of portraits from the exhibition will soon be released.
Bauer's passion for portraits prompted him to repeat the idea two years ago with the series "Portraits of Veteran Athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concept of Flamenco-people is slightly different, the photographer adds: "I really like photographing people, getting to know them and stepping into their lives for a longer or shorter moment.
In my opinion, the most difficult genre of photography is the portrait.
You meet people, people you don’t even know, or people who only take a few minutes to take photos.
But as a photographer, I always try to live up to my vision.
The exhibition, entitled Flamenco-people, selected from contemporary flamenco portraits, can be seen in the El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata Gallery, located in the Calle de la Mata 20 parallel to Alameda de Hércules until 16 October.
