Drunk Driving Drivers Will Be Forced to Install 'Alcolock'
The Interior Ministry would require the driver to install a device after three drunk driving offences that would prevent the vehicle from starting if the driver is drunk or does not blow into the device.
The proposal was presented in June and is now being dealt with by the Public Prosecutor’s Office, according to which the pilot project will last one year.
As the project aims to bring the vehicle back into circulation, the driver will also have to take part in a repeat course on traffic education.
In addition to the Chief Public Prosecutor’s Office, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Foundation for Automotive Safety Technology (FITSA) are also involved in the experiment.
According to statistics, 30-75% of drivers who have been arrested several times for drunk driving are back in their cars.
This would be prevented by Alcolock, because the system connected to the vehicle determines the alcohol level of the air blown into it. If it is higher than the allowed level, or if the driver has not blown into the device at all, the system will not allow the car to start.
The cost of an instrument costing more than EUR 1 000 would be borne by the infringer.
A 2007 study in the US showed that vehicles equipped with such instruments could reduce the number of violations by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure focuses on offences for two reasons: on the one hand, it is easier to prevent them from becoming offences,
on the other hand, it is easier to introduce, as the legal reform is being implemented in the usual way, while the necessary criminal reform would require a fundamental law amendment.
The instrument is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although in experimental mode it has already been installed in some industrial and public service vehicles.
The Chamber of Deputies will vote tomorrow on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party to install the system in school buses, following the example of France.
