Those who speak in dreams
Some kids talk at night.
I don’t mean those who wake up and tell me what happened to them that day, but those who talk while they sleep.
The phenomenon may seem frightening at first, but it is actually completely harmless.
This benign sleep disorder is called somniloquismus.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure some of you have been told that you spoke at night.
It can be completely rhapsodic in frequency (for example, it occurs only once in a disease with a high fever) or more regular (once a day, week or month), and usually the child does not remember anything the next day.
Its appearance cannot be traced back to a single cause.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal urination or sleepwalking, but this is not normal.
As mentioned above, it can be a symptom of a high-fever condition, or even a stressful situation or a state of heightened excitement.
It has been studied little so far.
The intensity of speech also varies greatly.
It may be quiet, it may consist of words and muttering that are not related, but in contrast, it may be in the form of shouting, crying, or longer speech.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist. The examination may reveal whether there is a problem that is causing great anxiety and therefore may offer a solution.
As mentioned above, this is a benign phenomenon and therefore there is no cure unless it is accompanied by another treatable form of sleep disorder (such as insomnia or stress).
However, there are a few things we can do, here is a bunch of preventive measures:
Make sure the child stays calm before going to bed.
Choose calming toys and avoid watching fear-inducing or more aggressive TV shows or series.
For children who are prone to nervousness or are more difficult to relax, we teach some relaxation methods to help them find inner peace.
This will help the child to sleep better.
If you start talking while you sleep, try to stay calm.
Remember, this is harmless for the child, and the next day they will remember nothing.
Helpful advice
Do not wake the child.
It would be unnecessary, because the child is not conscious, but he would be out of sleep.
In fact, even though he’s talking, he’s still sleeping and resting.
Remember, if the phenomenon is accompanied by intense anxiety several times, it is recommended to consult a specialist or explore what provokes a high level of anxiety in the child.
If he speaks clearly (this is a rarer case), do not start asking him questions in order to learn anything from him.
It would be useless anyway, since during sleep you are not so conscious to collect your thoughts.
On the other hand, you can only hear the speech, but you cannot see the dream images associated with it, so be careful with the interpretation of what you hear and possible conclusions.
Never tell a child that they can ask about their secrets at night.
Not even a joke.
This causes a great deal of anxiety.
So the most important thing is not to worry, as it is only a harmless episode of a few minutes.
