The blood is safe again.
Yesterday, Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation. President Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate, because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood donation companies in the world.
And most importantly, he managed to regain people’s trust, which was severely shaken by the tainted blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood supply treated by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Service was infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Canadian government, led by Judge Horace Krever, launched a formal investigation into the drama and the general outcry to shed light on the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to make recommendations to avoid similar incidents in the future.
While Judge Krever delayed submitting his report, some provinces set up their own committees aimed at designing a new blood-treatment system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Commission was responsible for this task.
The Gélineau and Krever reports led to the creation of two blood services in Canada: the Hema-Québec blood service for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Association for all other provinces and territories.
“When Héma-Québec started in 1998, only 38% of the population had confidence in Quebec’s blood supply system,” recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
"In the following years, however, as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field, we managed to regain the trust of the people." Décary proudly states that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population considered Héma-Québec to be reliable.
But Dr. Décary does not forget that “trust is a very fragile thing.”
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the principle of prudence.
During this period, several cases of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, have been discovered in Europe, says the doctor, who has been managing the company since its foundation in 1998.
"We had no idea that this disease was transmitted by blood.
Therefore, we relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports. According to this, if we are uncertain about this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, then we should apply exclusionary measures. In this case, it was Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which causes a change in the brain, so inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from persons who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was established beyond all doubt that the disease was transmitted by blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the principle of prudence.”
In 1999, a technique appeared on the market that allows a more sensitive diagnosis of HIV. This is the nucleic acid test (NAT), which is able to directly detect the virus itself in the blood of blood donors, and not the antibodies against the virus, on which previously used tests were built.
With the help of the NAT test, we were able to shorten the window period, which lasts from infection until we can detect the virus in the blood with the help of our technical tools, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
Thus, the risk of unknowingly infecting the blood was significantly reduced, as well as the risk of undetectable infection by blood donors.
These improvements have greatly reduced the risk of transmission of AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
“In other words, we would have to distribute 12 million blood products until someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Québec dispenses between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and for someone to become infected with HIV through a blood product.
I think that today anyone can safely accept or prescribe a blood transfusion in order to restore health, says the number one leader of Hema-Québec.
“The challenge for the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
You never know what new pathogens are going to enter the system.
It was only last year that the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood through insect bites.
Therefore, we have to be constantly on guard," continued Dr. Décary, then emphasized that in addition to emergency reserves, Hema-Québec must provide sufficient permanent reserves.
With the ageing of the population, the needs are also increasing.
Because anticancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has an impact on the stock of blood donors, as the number of people in the network who are able to donate blood is only 3% of the Quebec population.
However, every healthy person, at least 18 years of age, who meets the eligibility criteria, can give blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not accept blood because they are infected with, for example, AIDS or malaria, and those who have been to a country where malaria is spreading are not eligible to donate blood for a year.
“With this 3%, we have enough reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It's very rare for us to run out of supplies.
However, the number of blood donors should be increased as the existing ones age, because after a while they can no longer give blood.
But it is very difficult to persuade people to give blood, but it is even more difficult to keep them and persuade them to become regular blood donors.
In today’s fast-paced world, you don’t have an hour to go and give blood.” – Francine Décary
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissues, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which are used almost exclusively for severely burned people.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed, and frozen, and then placed at Hema-Québec, which also treats Québec’s only public stem cell bank.
The umbilical cord, once treated only as medical waste, produces blood that is rich in stem cells, making it possible to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago we celebrated the arrival of the 1,000th umbilical cord blood sample in our bank, and we plan to collect more than 1,000 new samples each year.
We will probably start offering them for organ transplants early next year,” said Décary, who said the cord blood removal program is very popular today.
“Many mothers are saddened that this is not possible” – indeed, it is because Hema-Québec is not in a position to make this complex and costly program available in every hospital in Quebec.
