The Orwellian Oratory of Barrick Gold
In the September 17 issue of Le Devoir, a letter was published from Patrick J. Garver, Deputy President and CEO of Barrick Gold Mine in Canada.
Garver claims that the world’s largest gold producer has filed a $6 million defamation suit against three authors and a small-money publishing company in an effort to initiate a so-called “public debate.”
Although judges are independent and impartial, their decisions, especially in defamation cases, are made not on the basis of the truth, but on the basis of the law.
Not surprisingly, Garver remained deeply silent about this fundamental difference.
Would the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate really be to destroy anyone whose point of view is contrary to his?
Regardless of the outcome of the lawsuit, the authors and publishers of the book Noir Canada must spend considerable amounts of money on defense and struggle in an unequal struggle with an army of lawyers backed by the almost inexhaustible resources of the mining industry on the other side.
In such an unequal struggle, moreover, the tactic of ruining the defendant and making a friendly agreement is often employed, which not only silences the opposite, but also intimidates those who would try to deal with the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have spoken to the public.
While in many other countries where Barrick Gold operates, this is not the case, in Canada the parties to the dispute usually do not strike each other with a stick, but tell their thoughts.
The mine would therefore have had to open its books and dossiers and prepare for a real debate in the press, media and publications, paying independent research groups that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn’t seem to trust the public and sweeps aside petitions and letters written to protect Noir Canada’s copyright.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can start a 'public' debate while ignoring the opinion of this public?
In the mind of the vice president, this word probably means only the well-paid lawyers, not the entire population of Canada: the meaning of the term is narrowed down.
In a democratic state, even those who denigrate others are entitled to freedom of speech.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that Noir Canada's authors and publishers are supported by the public, above all, because it condemns the mine's harsh practices.
The public is willing to listen to Barrick and form a verdict, but it would do so on the basis of civilized arguments rather than through a lawsuit aimed at silencing many. (By the way, in connection with the term "public debate", Barrick Gold recently called on the authors of Noir Canada in writing to refrain from using this term.)
In addition to Garver’s surrealistic expositions, Barrick Gold’s approach is an open attack on the freedom of academic research and the search for truth, which are the building blocks of any democratic society.
On the whole, the procedure denies the right to cite authentic sources, as well as the right to debate the facts and their interpretation, which form the basis of intellectual activities.
If, in a country like Canada, it is only possible to study and discuss issues that do not please the rich companies of today’s world, under the weight of litigation, who will have the courage to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wants an open and transparent debate, it could do so according to the scientific standards applied by Noir Canada’s authors.
You have the right to answer.
In our university circle, we have long been able to handle disputes, disagreements and conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s ill-advised approach shows that, contrary to his assertion, he has no desire to engage in open debate.
This represents a loss for both the university world and the institution of public debate in Canada. It is time for governments to finally put in place measures to limit legal proceedings launched with the aim of such abuse.
Wall Street Rescue: Republicans and Democrats Agree
Yesterday, the Republican and Democratic leaders of the Bush administration and Congress finally reached an agreement on the economic bailout, the largest such plan since the Great Depression.
The $700 billion plan, which aims to stem the financial crisis that has been raging on Wall Street for months, still needs to be approved by the two Houses of Congress.
The key elements of the plan are: more effective monitoring of implementation by Members; new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the earmarked public funds; new provisions to keep the number of houses seized due to non-payment; the right of access to the salaries of directors of companies receiving assistance.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican Judd Gregg announced the good news a few minutes before midnight yesterday after the two-day marathon session ended.
“We are making great progress toward a solution that will work effectively in the markets,” Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said in a statement.
“We’ve done everything we can to save the real economy and save American citizens from the current Wall Street crisis,” he said.
“The bottom line is that if we don’t do this, there will be a tremendous amount of shock, chaos and turmoil in Americans’ daily lives,” said Republican Rep. Judd Gregg.
The negotiations were accelerated in the last few hours for fear that another failure would have a detrimental effect on investor sentiment.
They gave themselves a deadline for the deal to open this morning.
The two presidential candidates who joined the negotiations late showed willingness to reach an agreement, but they expressed their disapproval of the fact that the situation has escalated to the end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has ascribed to himself the extension of the agreement with elements such as provisions related to the preservation of home ownership or the payment of directors of state-sponsored companies.
“When we ask taxpayers to take some extraordinary action because of other people’s irresponsibility, that’s not very welcome.
These steps are necessary,” he said in a televised interview.
And when his opponent, John McCain, was asked by another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, he replied, “I’d like to know the details, but I hope so.”
“From what I’ve read in broad outlines, it’s clear that this is something we all need to digest and move forward with.
The possibility of doing nothing is simply unacceptable,” he said.
Under the $700 billion plan, taxpayers' money would be used to buy the dubious claims of U.S. financial institutions and some risky, non-sellable assets.
The plan was preceded by a 14-month crisis triggered by the bursting of the real estate bubble, which led first to the collapse of risky real estate loans (secondary mortgages), then to the spread of other debt (commercial) securities, and finally to the freezing of liquid resources and the commotion of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft deal was struck by a group of Republican MPs last week.
We seem to have managed to get out of this dead end since the Democrats agreed that certain “toxic” assets of companies in difficulty should be secured by the government rather than bought up.
To satisfy all members of Congress, the plan also includes a provision that if the government has to bear losses under the program for five years, it can impose new taxes to recover its funds.
As part of the new plan, a $250 billion tranche would be paid first; a further $100 billion could follow if the president deems it necessary.
The remaining $350 billion would need to be approved by Congress.
In exchange for the aid, Washington acquires a stake in the subsidised companies, through which it receives dividends from the profits, which it can sell after the crisis has passed.
The federal government will have the possibility to delay the seizure of real estate to cover the mortgage loans covered by the plan. In addition, it can set the maximum value of wages and severance payments that can be paid to the managers of companies affected by the crisis.
The plan is expected to be approved by the House of Representatives today and by the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite their efforts, however, it is still not certain that the plan will be approved.
Yesterday, there were repeated objections to the plan among both Republicans and Democrats.
"It is absolutely clear that Washington is not hearing your voice," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told voters.
“We have serious financial problems.
Yes, there are solutions.
But there is nothing that will benefit the taxpayers.”
Brad Sherman, the Democratic leader of a small congressional group called the “skeptic faction,” presents things differently, but he comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred distinguished economists, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us asking Congress not to hurry and to look carefully at which path to take,” Sherman said.
At the same moment in Europe, it was again understood that this was a global crisis.
Following a crisis conference, the three Benelux states announced that they would nationalise part of the Fortis banking group for €11.2 billion (US$16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French BNP Paribas announced that it would not buy its near-bankruptcy competitor, after losing EUR 2 million (USD 2.9 billion) as a result of the crisis of secondary mortgages in the United States.
With 85,000 employees, Fortis is one of the 20 largest European banks and one of the 10 largest insurance companies.
"It's not wasted money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said.
"In return, we will gain the right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what depositors and households appreciate now that the situation promises to be precarious.”
Meanwhile, across the English Channel, the British government seems to be about to nationalize another bank that has been swept away by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all ongoing loans from Bradford and Bringley Bank, of which real estate loans amount to <0xC2><0xA3>41 billion (US$75.5 billion).
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it will acquire the subsidiaries and customer base of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank after Northern Rock to be nationalised by the British government since the start of the crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Farewell to the Idol of the Actors
His beautiful azure eyes were considered by some to be his main trump card, by others to be his main weakness.
Has the American actor ever gotten rid of his daffodil mirror?
Yes and no.
Because of his shyness, sensitivity and innate talent, he was also far from the loud style that is the essence of the true great monsters of the art world.
But what a huge course it has run!
Paul Newman, 83, died of lung cancer on Friday at his Connecticut estate, one of the last icons of the heyday of American cinema.
He was less monumental than Brando, whom he resembled, and who had long been his rival on the screen. In his role, he was more restrained and undoubtedly more vulnerable, but he also advocated freedom and the destruction of dramatic conventions.
From the mixing of blood, often extraordinary children are born.
Newman was born in 1925 in Ohio to a German Jewish father and a Hungarian mother.
European roots contributed to the birth of one of the symbolic figures of the American dream.
He did not think much of himself, which only increased his merits.
In the early 1950s, he studied drama at Yale University, then at Actor's Studio in New York City, before he exploded into the world of theatre, television, and shortly thereafter into the world of cinema.
In addition to being a champion of civil rights, he also finished second in the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans as a racing driver, and was considered a sex symbol, although he had been happily married to actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
We shall never know what the dark sides of this mysterious, aloof, devoted actor, who hated the glamour of show business, have been, and will always remain, a mystery.
He was an honest man in the best sense of the word.
The death of Paul Newman at the end of the week has shocked movie fans: we can only see him in his big roles on the black screen of memories.
Looking through his oeuvre, we can see the seventh American art: cinema has been constantly changing for more than fifty years.
We remember the charming cowboy "Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid" (1969) and the estranged young man from his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor), in the role of whom we saw the Tennessee Williams cover of "Cat on a Hot Tin Roof" in 1958.
In recent times (1990), we can remember him as the sensitive Mr. Bridge, who is faced with the fact that his marriage has not lived up to his expectations.
Paul Newman has seen many other faces in his films.
In Robert Wise's "Someone Upstairs", he played the turbulent criminal-boxer Rocky Graziano, the role that started Newman's acting career in 1956, originally intended for James Dean and taken over after his death.
He also played a sympathetic criminal in the brilliant film "The Great Controversy", which won an Oscar for Best Picture in 1973.
In Robert Rossen's brilliant 1961 film The Swindler, he played a bitter, vengeful billiard player, and returned in a similar role in Martin Scorsese's 1987 film The Color of Money, for which he received his only Oscar nomination in nine nominations.
Times are changing, but it's always the same face: that's who he was.
He's always been like that.
The period of his career was marked by periods of change.
He is best known for his role as Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional ice hockey coach, in George Roy Hill's 1977 cult film The Icebreakers.
His fans saw him in the 1994 Coen Brothers' "The Great Leap Forward."
Sam Mendes' 2003 film, Path of Perdition, was his last appearance as an Irish mob boss.
Unlike many movie legends who left the screen relatively soon, Newman remained in the spotlight for a long time, although he condemned Hollywood for its glamour, luxury, and hypocrisy.
French film director Bertrand Tavernier did not without humor view it as a "living rebuttal of underplaying": he thought his play was too powerful.
The profession, however, was not always kind to the handsome Paul Newman, who for a long time just fell into the lap of the film roles.
However, he played young and successful characters less often: rather, he played figures living on the fringes of society - neurotic, alcoholic, malignant or hopeless - whose drift and rebellion he was able to reproduce with perfect authenticity.
As a director, Newman showed a lesser-known face: a truly modest and sensitive man deep down in his soul.
In the 1968 film "Rachel, Rachel" (an adaptation of the novel by Canadian author Margaret Laurence), he and his wife Joanne Woodward starred in a delicate portrait of a melancholy woman.
In the 1984 film "Harry and His Son", he pays tribute to his son, Scott, who died of a drug overdose.
Yesterday, Newman was remembered by countless admirers, and his close friend and longtime comrade-in-arms, Robert Redford (with whom they played together in "The Great Controversy" and "Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid") lamented, "His presence has made my life and the world a better place.
Generosity and the joy of being: that was the secret to the vibrant personality of this great actor that we have now lost.
Alongside his legendary career, he blurs his focus on civil rights, the environment, independent filmmaking, and criticism of Hollywood's excesses.
Many times we could see his picture smiling on the packaging of sauces, sauces, biscuits and other foods. He did it with a rather bad taste in his mouth, although in the beginning he thought it was funny.
However, the proceeds from such sales have always been transferred to his foundation for children with the disease.
Newman never rested on his laurels: he remained committed to the profession throughout.
In a letter to her five daughters, she wrote: "Your father was and has always been incredibly grateful for his star of fortune.
It was a privilege to be here.”
It is also a privilege for us to follow the career of such a brilliant and generous American artist.
He was a model citizen, above all.
What was produced at Zuschlag & Tsai’s invoice factory?
Soon, on October 8, the trial of János Zuschlag and his associates will begin.
The politician and his associates are accused of fraud and other crimes, including forgery of documents, that have caused particularly significant damage, and that have been committed in a criminal organization on a continuous and commercial basis.
According to the prosecutor’s office, the tender funds were used for their own purposes, and the performance of tasks was often proven by false invoices.
The state and local government funds - in total about 65 million forints - migrated partly into the coffers of the Young Left and partly into the pockets of certain individuals.
The method described by the investigative authority was that the funds received were collected on the basis of cost accounts that were not backed by actual performance, and the associations never complied with the commitments they had made.
