The psychology of overbidding: why do we give out more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overvalue the goods.
Neurological-economic foundations for this known—and seemingly irrational—behaviour have been explored by neurologists and economists at New York University.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people don’t want to be beaten in a type of competition like eBay’s auction, so they tend to pay too high a price.
The research tried to map the neural pattern of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers participated in a lottery and the other group participated in a player auction, while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method to examine the subjects’ active brain regions.
In both games, the participants could win money, but during the auction game, in which an essential element is the overbidding of the other party, the striatum, a subcortical complex, was activated intensively when the game was lost.
This area of the brain, among other functions, plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the surge in the price can be explained by avoiding a violent reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In it, three groups bet against one partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they placed their bets.
Another group was promised an additional $15 if they were to win the game.
The third group had just received $15 before the auction, but the members of the group also lost that money in the event of a losing auction.
The only difference between the two groups was that they emphasized winning for one group and losing for the other.
However, proving the neurologists' hypothesis, members of the team playing "against loss" were willing to bet higher than the control and "winning" groups.
“These results cannot be deduced from any pre-existing economic theory.
Until now, they have only explained the phenomena of the auction with the joy of winning and avoiding risks.
Neurological imaging alone has helped to resolve the conflict between these two theories by providing a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
About half a billion people around the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death in Hungary.
The number of people infected with hepatitis at home is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, the reason for which: patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the common name for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, they are characterized by hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases they cause are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogen, are transmitted in two main forms: hepatitis A and E through the gastrointestinal tract (for example, with infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (vomit, vaginal discharge, saliva).
Travellers should definitely protect themselves against A and B viruses, there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating an infected food, generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal discomfort, nausea.
After that, the yellowness visible on the skin and the whites of the eyes develops, the stool is light, the urine becomes dark, the healing can take two to three weeks.
Worldwide, one million people die each year from a more serious form of the disease, hepatitis B liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people receive medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, because the pathogen insidiously destroys the cells of the liver, in many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20-30 years.
Thus, it is very important to carry out early prevention and regular screening tests.
Three groups have significantly higher than average rates of this disease: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users, and people with tattoos.
There are currently 200 million people worldwide infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory test, it is advisable to consult your GP if you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
When recognized in time, the disease can be cured, the virus can be eliminated from the body, thus, the infectivity ceases and the development of cancer can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first celebrated in 2004 by organizations representing patients around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to the chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God feel any less pain?
According to a recent study, religious faith acts as a painkiller that may have eased the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment to investigate how belief in God affects people’s perception of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
The study involved electroshocking 12 Catholics and an equal number of atheists, all studying a painting of the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholics were able to rule out much of the pain.
Thanks to the technology that scans the human brain, Catholics have also been able to activate the part of the brain responsible for controlling pain.
The study is the first in a series of studies involving academics, as well as scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
The study was conducted by attaching a sparking device to the subject’s left hand, which provided the electroshock.
The researchers asked the participants to look closely at two paintings, the 17th-century Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato and the 15th-century Lady with Hermeline painted by Leonardo da Vinci.
The authors of the study hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would bring about a religious state among the believers, while the da Vinci image was chosen because it was not too different from the others and was thought to have a calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner machine, receiving 20 electroshocks in four consecutive parts while either looking at the religious theme or the general picture.
Catholics reported that when they saw the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe" as if they were "taken care of" and "calm down, they were at peace."
When they looked at the religious-themed picture, they reported 12 percent less pain than when they saw Leonardo’s work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself was involved in the study, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerful image, even for atheists, you just need to find the right photo.
“We should find an image that they feel very positively about, like a mother or a father,” he said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the findings.
“The practice of faith should and in many cases will change our personality,” Wright added.
After the excellent results, the only question is: if Leonardo or a similar-calibre painter is shown a picture of one of the Madonnas to the faithful, what effect would it have on their pain control?
Would seeing the quality of the Virgin Mary mean even better results?
You are what you share about yourself
On his tenth birthday, Google can tell you: it can be found in people’s pockets at least as much as above their heads in the sky; he knows where they vacationed, what specialist appointments they attend and what they are interested in.
And that's still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's top people.
As for the skeptics who draw parallels with the Orwellian nightmare, they don’t see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main goal is to collect more personal information about its users, which is necessary to keep up with the original goal of the founders of Google, which was “to gather all the information in the world.”
According to the CEO of Google, after ten years of world subversion, the company is still at the beginning of being able to handle all the information.
Asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt said he wanted Google to answer questions such as “what should I do tomorrow?” and “what kind of work would really suit me?” – but until then, software can’t answer such simple questions because it doesn’t know enough about its users.
Not all Internet users are aware of the fact that during internet searches, the search words are recorded exactly, from which IP address they searched and to which page the visitors left after the search.
For example, Personalized Search, launched two years ago, allows users to store their own surfing history, look back at what they were looking for, what they clicked on, and in the long run it will generate much more personalized results for them - the same logic will be used in Recommendations, with which the system will offer us products and services based on our previously stated and recorded preferences.
What if they use my data against me if they look at what I do?, users who are worried about seeing Google’s data monopoly ask.
In most cases, the potential power represented by the company can be daunting, not the guilt, fear of punishment, desire for freedom, or even rebellion against power that triggers counter-reactions among Internet users.
However, it is a confirmed fact that all searched terms are not only recorded, but in justified cases they can also be passed on to third parties, in such cases the privacy rights of internet users are not protected.
Perhaps the loudest example of this in recent times was the coordinated action against pedophiles in Brazil, in which Google provided the Brazilian government with information about pedophiles from the social network Orkut, which it maintains.
Internet users concerned about privacy rights, however, may have sighed in May when the company, along with the EFF, successfully proved its case in court against the FBI: according to which Google cannot be forced to disclose any information secretly requested by the FBI by any point in the Constitution in the future.
(At the same time, the federal government has successfully fought off some 50,000 web addresses and thousands of search terms, which it has obtained by citing the ratification of the Child Protection Act passed years earlier, but it has not managed to obtain the individual user search lists and the full two-month list of websites and keywords.)
Google’s judgment is rather contradictory: it is scolded by those who are afraid to give their personal data away because they feel that their intimate sphere and privacy are being eroded by the fact that they are starting to use Google’s services and are rebelling against them in a way that is worthy of the multinationals that shine in a conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its raucous network of computer enthusiasts, activists, and users in many countries see them as the next generation of big companies, the “cool corporation,” unlike its rival, Microsoft, which is considered a conqueror of the world because of Windows, no matter how hard they both struggle for the same goal.
This may be because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not charge its users for identification codes, it does not charge for its applications, and the open, free, constantly updated source code and software package seems to be much more accessible, younger and cooler than the official software giant’s practices.
However, it can also happen because geeks have a clear understanding of the very problematic relationship between personality rights and the Internet, which has been brought about by one of the most frequently cited keywords of recent years, web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, about deliberately leaving clues behind and taking advantage of the communication channels available to us, and while these vary from person to person, the point is the same: we show ourselves.
An average young person can also manage profiles on multiple social media sites, from Facebook to Xanga, connect them to other services such as Twitter or last.fm, which lists their musical habits, and connect them all to tracking systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, and they can also manage a blog on which their latest photo galleries are automatically displayed on Facebook or Flickr.
While we can read about several exemplary cases that shed light on it: a girlfriend can easily find out from the morning photo stream of a group of friends that a fraudulent friend spent the evening with, or she can fire an employee of a company just because she writes her honest opinion about the top management in her blog: one thing is for sure, the concept of privacy has been completely re-evaluated by now.
Those who live online are made up of what they show themselves to be able to formulate the basic tenets behind the behavior of today’s young people.
Anyone who wants to hide something, or at least avoid the Google monopoly, can do so (starting with Scroogle, which uses Google’s search system, but leaves no trace at the same time).
For example, the number of people who deliberately choose not to sign up for social networking sites so that they cannot be found can be replaced by alternative versions of Google’s online applications, from word processor to image manager and newsreader, which are not tied to huge server parks and do not make us the best profile ever.
The public is not so secretly waiting for Google to reveal its teeth.
With a current value of $156 billion, the company is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising platforms are threatening the revenue of advertising agencies, and the ever-accelerating introduction of services is causing serious headaches not only for Microsoft, but also for many other software developers.
Critics, however, also find counterpoints that may seem disturbing: for example, the top management completely rejected the protest of the employees after doubling the fee of the company kindergarten, the company management found too expensive to feed the employees multiple times a day for the Chinese company, but according to the Chinese, all of this is dwarfed by the fact that Google was still in charge of the Chinese government in 2006.
One of the company’s internal rules is that they don’t announce a new service in advance, only when it is ready for use, but it is certain that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years may move the world to a new point: while some believe that our previous Google book and magazine scanning and archiving project with our health care profile has taken on such a scale that the company will soon have to face the US Supreme Court’s system of Health.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database could be good material for the next generation of sci-fi writers, and the popular Cory Doctorow short story Scroogled dot Orwellian overtones describe a future in which a person can only be approached alarmingly well from Google’s data.
