The Bumblebee's Flight Is Imitated by the Intelligent Car
What would be the best way to develop technologies to avoid collisions, if not to imitate the barrier sensors that occur in the world of nature?
The bees, for example.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, bumblebees provided Nissan engineers with the strategic starting point for building the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C bio-inspired auto-robot control system, a robotic mini-car with bee features, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that eliminates all collisions.
During the flight, each bee forms its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective shell, explained Kazuhhiro Doi, technology PR and R&D brand manager at the exhibition.
An important role is played by the complex eye of the uterus, which can see at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions.
To replicate the function of the complex eye, the engineers used the idea of a laser rangefinder.
This detects obstacles within 2 meters in a 180-degree field of view ahead of the BR23C, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into a collision avoidance operation.
In a fraction of a second, the obstacle is detected, and then the autobot changes direction immediately, imitating the movements of the bee, by turning its wheels as much as necessary to avoid a collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoidance maneuver is completely instinctive.
“If this were not the case, the auto-robot would not be able to react fast enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the auto-robot project.
You need to react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety shield, a layer within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process has to reflect what a bee does in order to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot be directed upwards, downwards, or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the endless possibilities available to bees to avoid other bees, only rotational motion and acceleration, as well as deceleration, were used here as the option available to the autobot.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer life than the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, the instinctive intelligent response is important, not the ability to process data, much less store it.
This device only needs to process and respond to a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so you constantly use only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There is no need for gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of an instant-avoidance technology that Nissan estimates could be in production vehicles within ten years.
An additional application is the integration of the unit with the GPS-satellite navigation system to guide the driver to the specified destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
