There is a written version of the multi-tranche $700 billion economic rescue package law, which aims to buy bad loans from banks.
In the first round, half of the amount is spent.
In a new round of talks that will last until after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders have come to a close in the days-long debate surrounding the $700 billion bailout, Reuters reported.
“We have made serious progress,” said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic Speaker of the US House of Representatives.
The compromise on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Finance Minister Henry Paulson, speaking about the result of the compromise, said that the program will work and be effective, but more needs to be done. According to Pelosi, this is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the cart of the economy around.
The written version of the package was released before the opening of the Asian markets on Sunday night at 8:00 a.m. Washington time (i.e. 2 a.m. Central European time on Monday), but did not cause a spectacular run on the stock exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will vote on the draft law on the program, which is called the Economic Emergency Stabilization Act of 2008.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night and the White House welcomed the news of the deal.
“We are pleased with the progress made last night and appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy,” White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
The program deviates from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend $700 billion on one-to-one purchases of low-quality, credit-backed securities.
Now, in the first round, up to half of the $700 billion can be spent, with $250 billion immediately spent after Congress is expected to vote on Monday, from which the Treasury Department buys credit-backed, poorly rated securities, and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president’s decision.
The program will be overseen by a special board, including the president of the Federal Reserve.
Spending the other half of the 700 billion depends on a new resolution from Congress.
Under the law, the Treasury Department can use a combination of tactics: you can buy bad loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities at the same time, as well as other types of "toxic" loans.
Purchases can be made through auctions and directly, the ministry said.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the Treasury guarantees assets of concern, for which the companies will pay a fee commensurate with the expected damages.
Henry Paulson said the law would provide the necessary funds to meet the urgent needs of the U.S. financial system, whether it’s buying bad assets on a large scale, insuring them, or avoiding the systemic risk of a large financial institution collapsing.
“We will take the necessary steps to be ready to implement the law as soon as it is signed into law,” he added.
On the other hand, the bosses of banks in trouble and waiting for government assistance can expect their exit money, which the overseas slang simply calls a golden parachute, to be restricted by the government.
Salaries are restricted only in certain cases, and the limits depend on the way in which the Ministry of Finance provides assistance.
The restriction essentially means that if the ministry buys by auction, an additional tax will be levied on the golden parachute unless the bailout banker is retired.
When buying bad loans outright, the government will aggressively intervene to ensure that its management funds are not exaggerated.
As part of the picture, the existing golden parachute contracts will remain unchanged, with the restriction applying only to new ones, in order to encourage participation in the program.
This is the first time in U.S. history that there will be a legal restriction on CEO remuneration, said House Financial Services Committee Chairman Barney Frank.
In addition, the state acquires the right to acquire shares in the banks participating in the scheme, thus reducing the risk for taxpayers, as they can ultimately win the transaction once the economy and the bank that was rescued recovers.
The bill will require the president to submit a proposal to Congress over the next five years on how to return taxpayers' expected losses from the financial sector.
On both sides, of course, there were those who expressed doubts about the plan.
“It’s not what the American people are asking us to do, it’s not protecting taxpayers’ dollars,” said Republican Congressman Darrell Issa of California.
His Ohio Democrat colleague Mary Kaptur said the measures were being pushed by the same people responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
The domestic sales prices of industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, reports KSH.
The prices of industrial export sales were 1.1 percent higher than in July 2008, and decreased by 3.9 percent year-on-year.
As a result of domestic and export price changes, industrial producer prices were 0.7 percent higher than in the previous month and 3.2 percent higher than a year earlier.
The domestic sales prices of industry increased only minimally, by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of manufacturing sectors also increased slightly, by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The biggest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather goods and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), mainly due to the 4.6 percent and 2.5 percent monthly price increase in the bag and strap manufacturing and footwear manufacturing sectors.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6%).
There was a price decrease in the sectors of petroleum processing (1.4 percent), electrical machinery and instrument production (0.9 percent) and - to a minimum - wood processing (0.1 percent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In the other manufacturing sectors, price growth was between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector, which plays a significant role in the domestic sales of industry, prices increased by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the delayed impact of the official gas price increase implemented from 1 July.
In a twelve-month comparison, in terms of domestic sales of the manufacturing sectors, prices increased the most in the petroleum processing sector (32.4%).
The manufacture of metalworking products increased by 13.2 percent, and the manufacturing of food, beverages and tobacco by 11 percent.
The price decrease occurred in the manufacture of textiles and textile articles (2.5%) and the manufacture of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3%).
In the other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price increase ranged from 0.6 percent to 9.1 percent.
In the manufacturing industry as a whole, prices increased by 10.2 percent over the past year.
The prices of the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7 percent higher than a year earlier.
Among the intended groups of industries, domestic sales showed the highest monthly price increase in August in the manufacturing of capital goods (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, while in the energy and downstream sectors, prices remained unchanged compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the biggest price increase was observed in the energy and downstream sectors (16.8%).
In the consumer goods sectors, we recorded a 6.8 percent price increase and in the capital goods sector, a 1.4 percent price decrease.
The industry’s export sales prices in HUF increased by 1.1 percent in August, compared to the previous month, and decreased by 3.9 percent in 12 months.
In one month, our domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro and 7.1 percent against the dollar, and by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar compared to August 2007.
