Workplace accidents: Napolitano says prevention is more important than anything else
In Italy, 2,500 accidents at work occur every day, of which 3 lead to death and 27 to permanent disability.
According to the data of the occupational accident insurance company, there were nearly 1,200 deaths at workplaces in 2007.
The figures show the seriousness of a phenomenon that is still one of the most common causes of death and claims almost twice as many victims as homicide.
Today, for the 58th time, Anmil is organising the Day of Victims of Accidents at Work, traditionally held in all Italian counties on the second Sunday of October, to draw the attention of institutions, social organisations and the mass media to this dramatic problem.
"The alarming data provided by Anmil, as well as the tragic events of the last few days, confirm that prevention plays a particularly important role in workplace accidents," President Giorgio Napolitano said in a message to Pietro Mercandelli, President of the National Association of Workplace Accident Invalids.
The head of state sincerely praised the association’s “persevering commitment to the prevention of accidents at work, the protection of the interests of workers in accidents, the assistance of the victims’ family members and the sensitization of public opinion”.
“These tragedies, which are natural and frankly shared by everyone, and which are of such a size, arouse the interest of the media and the general public, but in reality we have to face dramatic cases every day, which are repeated over and over again.”
Napolitano openly admits: "There is undoubtedly a lack of resources, the funding of education and information is crucial.
Initiatives within the school aimed at directly educating young people who are about to enter the world of work are particularly important.
It is our duty to maintain interest in the phenomenon, not to allow attention to be lost to the social importance of the issue, and to have more effective legislation that must be enforced.
For his part, the President of the House of Commons, Gianfranco Fini, stressed “the grave social significance of fatal accidents at work, which weighs on the conscience of all of us, and the institutions are required to put an end to it as soon as possible.”
"The data on accidents at work show a slight improvement, but the number of deaths of this kind is still incredibly high," said Pietro Mercandelli, president of Anmil.
"But we don't want this downward trend to be accompanied by a downward trend of attention, because it's precisely when attention is slack that the greatest tragedies occur."
"We believe that, at a general level, we are still not doing all we can to combat this phenomenon, which could be solved through a complex programme of action.
