Mr Mercandelli then criticised the "gradual deterioration of the safety net for victims of accidents at work" and the "aid trend towards which the system has drifted in recent years".
“The aim is therefore to give back to the workers the security provided by insurance, because the fate of the victims of an accident cannot depend on the arbitrary and sometimes divisive measures of the legislators.”
MP3 players can cause hearing loss
Permanent hearing loss can be caused by listening to portable playback devices such as MP3 players for extended periods of time and at high volume levels.
In its report published in Brussels, the European Commission, citing an opinion published today by the EU's Scientific Committee on New and Newly Identified Health Risks (SCENIHR).
“The report shows that 5 to 10 percent of people who listen to their portable music player at a high volume for more than one hour per day for five years may have permanent hearing loss,” the report said.
“It is worrying that young people who use high-volume portable music players and mobile phones on a large scale and often do not realise that they can cause irreversible hearing damage,” said Meglena Kuneva.
“Scientific surveys indicate an undisputed risk that we urgently need to respond to,” he added.
The most important task is to inform consumers and disseminate this information widely.
In the light of this opinion, we also need to review existing control systems to ensure that they are effective and keep pace with the latest technologies."
Brussels has asked the independent scientific committee to examine the problem in the light of the proliferation of personal music players and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise.
"Researchers confirm that there is cause for concern, and the European Commission, in cooperation with Member States and stakeholders, is ready to explore possible measures to protect children and young people exposed to noise from portable players and similar devices," he concluded.
The current European safety standard specifies a maximum noise level of 100 dB that can be emitted by personal music players, but there is growing concern about data on hearing loss resulting from the excessive use of such sound sources.
At the same time, there are solutions, such as reducing the level and duration of noise pollution, which can significantly reduce these hearing impairments.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee states that users of portable players who listen to music at high volume levels (over 89 decibels) for five hours a week are exposed to noise levels above the current maximum levels for noise at work.
If a person listens to music for a long time in similar circumstances, there is a risk of permanent hearing loss after five years.
This affects about 5-10% of users of portable devices, which could mean 2.5-10 million people in the EU.
Rome, Alemanno set up commission for the future of the capital
Starts today, runs until March, results are expected in June.
This is the timetable set by the Metropolitan Municipality for the operation of the "Future of the Capital of Rome" committee, which met this morning at its new headquarters behind the baths of Caracalla.
Over the next six months, President Antonio Marzano and the other 49 members of the Commission will develop Rome’s policies.
After the closing speech in March, the study and the plans will be evaluated in the general assembly and the municipal committee, so that the strategic plan of the capital, officially approved by the Municipality and Mayor Gianni Alemanno, can be submitted in June.
“It is a completely independent commission, in which all political, social and cultural ideas are represented,” Alemanno emphasizes, “and its task is to draw up proposals for Rome’s development ideas on which the political decision-makers, i.e. the General Assembly and the Municipal Commission, can rely.
We are not talking about any conflict of competence, we just wanted a platform where great plans can be made for the good of Rome.
In March, after completing its work, the committee will be dissolved because it has a fixed-term mandate.
In June, we will submit a strategic plan based on the work of the "Future of the Capital of Rome" committee, the Mayor said.
To those who consider the Commission's work superfluous, arguing that the opinion it has set up is not binding, Alemanno replies: "It all depends on the work that the Commission will do and the quality of the proposals it will put on the table.
If the standard proves to be adequate, as in France for the Attali Commission, which I am sure is the case for Rome, its contribution will play an important role.
The power of politics is often dissipated in dealing with day-to-day affairs, as well as in dealing with urgent cases that arise from time to time.
We, on the other hand, take a long-term view and plan for the longer term and are committed to Rome’s development and future.”
The mayor of Rome would like to make it clear that “this Commission cannot be considered a useless “head of water” because it will be completely free, it will not cost the citizens of Rome a single euro, but instead serves as an inspiration and aims to attract the best minds of the capital”.
“We need an open-ended and flexible strategic framework that will enable our city to make the leap in quality it so desperately needs, thinking unitedly about its future,” he said.
The future, in which the Mayor of Rome emphasizes that “it will not only be limited to the current framework of self-government, but will look much further”, is not only the future metropolis and the status of the capital, but also “the role that it can and must play as the capital of Rome, of Europe and of the Mediterranean”.
