Elites in Danger
The phenomenon was already felt a few days ago, when the House of Representatives did not vote for the $700 billion rescue package put forward by the White House: a significant number of Americans were and still are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
As evidenced by yesterday’s New York Times, which reports that the current crisis has created a rupture within the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided between the traditional, subdued East Coast approach, which supports federal institutions and business circles, and the growing anti-Washington and anti-financial world trend in the Central and Southern states.
This line was expressed in a critical manner during the House vote mentioned in the introduction.
However, the above event is only one of the significant changes that the ongoing economic restructuring predicts or allows to be seen, not only in the United States, but throughout the Western world, and perhaps even beyond.
It seems that the crisis, both in the USA and in Europe, is only speeding up those phenomena that have been latent for a long time and which are solidifying in this new atmosphere and are finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the re-establishment of the dual category of state sovereignty, in connection with a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis affects those banking and financial institutions that, although they have close relations with the rest of the world, are primarily, and to a fairly large extent, attracting people and families who live in a single country, a single state.
This, in turn, poses a direct political difficulty for those in government: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people who are also voters.
Thus, while the crisis appears to be global in economic terms, it is almost exclusively national in political terms.
Political internationalism seems to be essentially off-line: the European Union is a shining example of this, unable to define a single political direction, juggling different interests and different national strategies.
So everyone is waiting for the intervention, the rescue package, the recovery and the new rules from the individual national governments, but most of all for the opening up of the funds: because only the individual states have economic resources, financial resources that are capable of putting things right.
They have the means and the authority to use them: under certain circumstances, they have two invaluable resources that probably no other market and no international organisation will ever possess to such an extent.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed by the crisis on the nation-state is fully in line with the fact that economic growth in recent times attaches increasing importance to a factor that is closely related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had already entered the abstract world of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, and we were convinced that the global financial world was destined to rule the world, we had to realize that our future increasingly depended on things that were not at all abstract, such as water, crops and oil.
Things that can be transported from one side of the planet to the other, yet they are completely bound to a limited place, a territory.
So the man who controls the area has a lot more trump cards than the man who, unfortunately, was born in a place where there is no crop, no oil, and no water.
This brings me to the second novelty, which suggests a kind of fault line.
Whoever says territory, state, government, necessarily also says politics, in other words, leadership.
From this point of view, the economic crisis seems to be producing two parallel phenomena:
On the one hand, the objective recognition of the need for credible leadership, someone who can take control of events.
On the other hand, the current leadership, especially the economic leaders, is bringing a complete loss of credit, who have proved completely inadequate and have proven that there is still a lot of vague ground ahead of them.
Together, the two are even more profound and, in a sense, more disturbing: a sense of loss of credibility, impatience, inadequacy and isolation that affects the entire leadership elite in more and more Western countries.
It seems, therefore, that there is a growing belief among the population that the era of the social elite, which has been at its peak so far, has come to an end, even before they have embraced their actions, their experiences, their way of life, their culture, in the complex sense of the word.
In a word, the demand for leadership, in a veiled form, fosters a diverse but strong delegitimation movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system. This may be manifested in the unanticipated "revolts" of the voters, or in the sudden changes in the mood of the American Congress in recent times.
It seems that the traditional elite, with its parties, programs, and we might even say that together with its customs, press, and renowned intellectuals, it is less and less able to understand, and therefore less and less to represent, what has been happening in the deeper layers of Western society for some time.
Nevertheless, to speak of “the impending revolt of the masses” would, frankly, be an exaggeration.
But it doesn't hurt to walk with your eyes open.
