With fruit juice, it's forbidden!
Be careful with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These thirst-quenching drinks with a high vitamin content, which are especially popular in the summer, if they are introduced into the body together with certain life-saving drugs, alter their absorption, increasing or decreasing their effect, depending on the case.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, spoke at the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia about the risks associated with the combination of canned or fresh fruit juices and certain medications. The professor announced at the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia that a glass of grapefruit, orange or apple juice could reduce the absorption of certain life-saving drugs, preventing their beneficial effects and putting them at risk.
Grapefruit juice has been on the stand before the defendants when it was found to be able to increase the effects of some antibiotics, antihistamines, anti-anxiety drugs, heart rhythm regulators and nerve medicines to levels considered toxic.
DANGEROUS MEDICINES - Two years ago, the Italian Institute of Pharmacy itself published the news in its official gazette and also warned doctors and patients to take the risks associated with this combination seriously and to watch what they drink when taking drugs such as Diazepam or Methadone.
GRAPEFRUIT – According to the researchers, both orange and apple juice contain substances that inhibit the effectiveness of medications.
A long list of active substances, the absorption of which is hindered by grapefruit and other juices, could be listed.
Michele Carruba, professor of pharmaceuticals at the State University of Milan, points out: “Such discoveries are usually immediately reported to the various national and international pharmaceutical institutes, which, if necessary, make sure to change the information on the product’s leaflet.
That’s why you should always read the information on the medicine you’re taking, and if something isn’t clear, don’t let it get to you, but ask your doctor or pharmacist clearly.”
