Open Office, third edition was worth the "anti-Microsoft" package
Today, OpenOffice.org 3.0, an open-source application suite designed to increase personal productivity, is being released as a free alternative to Microsoft Office, targeting an increasing number of people, from home users to office users, from the liberal professions to public administrations.
After nearly a year of work under the supervision of SUN Microsystem and by volunteer developers, the new Open Office brings more new features to the public: in addition to the welcome screen and the redesigned, less spartan user interface, it also offers more essential features, such as compatibility with Apple’s Mac OS X operating system and support for the new ISO-standard ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2.
Special attention has been paid to compatibility with Office 2007 so that Open Office can open Microsoft documents with the new extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Another interesting feature is the specific functionality of some modules, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations. This can be useful when sending files by email. Another feature supports importing PDF files into a graphics module, while maintaining a page-place layout.
In the same interface, you can also create "hybrid PDF" documents, which combines the typical Adobe format with spreadsheet or word processing elements.
Sharing within applications has also undergone several improvements: the spreadsheet supports the shared use of workbooks, but prevents overwriting of each other's work. Each employee's comments are marked in a different color, which helps to make them easier to recognize during the verification phase.
Some companies are already working on making some of OpenOffice’s features available from the Internet (on the cloud), so the final version is likely to be released in the coming weeks.
The Italian version can be downloaded from http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html.
In addition to the usual Windows and Mac OS operating systems, the software package is also available for Linux.
Upon request, we can take over the installation CD at home or at our workplace.
Free is probably the biggest attraction when it comes to the home application, but the Open Office suite is now trying to get into the business sector as well, as it can count on a number of administrative and school projects.
There is also a lack of education, consulting and service services ideal for small and medium-sized enterprises, which can open up new business prospects.
Open Office consists of five core modules: Writer, a word processor for Word; Calc, a spreadsheet to replace Excel; Impress, for PowerPoint-like presentations; Dbase, the most well-known, similar to Access database management; and finally Draw, the graphics module.
