Students suffer from expensive rents, a room can cost up to 900 euros
The market for student accommodation is not affected by the crisis.
According to a recent survey by Sunia, the Union of Tenants, a student can pay up to €900 for a single room in Milan, €700 in Florence, €650 in Naples and €600 in Rome.
"The scale of the phenomenon is now so staggering that, because of the huge costs that families have to bear, it prevents large numbers of students from learning," explains Laura Mariani, head of the study office at Sunia. "The high demand from students in these cities has distorted the market to such an extent that a general price increase has also started to affect local residents."
In most cases, real estate offers also contain a number of irregularities: unregistered contracts with no rent limitation, with linked sublease.
According to Sunia, an exceptional measure would be needed to allow prices to be maximised by revising the tax system.
The survey shows that in Milan, around Brianza, a bed costs 450 euros; a single room costs 650 euros (near Bande Nere) to an average of 800 euros (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera) or 900 euros (near Vittoria).
In Florence, a bed costs an average of 350/400 euros, and a room costs about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where most students live near the university, a single bed costs €250/280 for a double room and €370-500 for a single room.
In Rome, in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), they charge about 600 euros for a single bed and 450 for a double bed.
Slightly cheaper (550 euros for a single room) are the prices of other universities around (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
Some savings can be made in the suburbs: 300 euros for a bed and 450 for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and other similar districts.
For a bed in Naples, 300/450 euros is charged, for a room from 400 to 600 euros. The price range is the highest in the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, a single bed costs 250/350 euros and at least 350 euros for a single room.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they represent a greater weight within the city budget.
In cities such as Perugia, where students from outside the EU often seek accommodation, there is another anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is about 25 to 30 percent higher than that charged to Italian tenants.
Good-bye, old Cinema Paradiso, the time of the old cinema halls is over in the cities
Traditional cinemas close in favor of Multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas, a blind city, is like a face without eyes.”
The images by director Giuseppe Tornatore are a powerful illustration of what is happening in the Italian cities and rural regions.
The displacement of cinemas - the emergence of large multi-screen cinemas in the suburbs and the consequent withering away of single-screen cinemas in city centres - seems to be an inevitable and irreversible process, but at the same time it bears all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
When places full of history and memories disappear, "it's like having a friend go away, an acquaintance with whom we shared our journey and many experiences," says Cinema Paradiso director. The film, which 20 years ago may have been an Oscar award, as well as the lost Grand Prix of the Cannes Festival Tornatoré, tells the lyrical story of a small-town movie after a yearning,
The figures provided by the largest association of operators, Anec, are clear: 316 traditional cinemas closed in the last five years. The biggest losses were recorded in cinemas in large cities: 10 cinemas closed in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin, and 5 in Palermo.
Emilia-Romagna is in the lead among the most affected regions, losing 82 one-room cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And that the proliferation of multiplexes is responsible for their disappearance is no better evidence than the fact that Italy has the highest number of newly opened multi-room cinemas in these three regions: in the last five years, the number of cinemas has increased by 195 in Lombardy, by 81 in Tuscany and by the same amount in Emilia-Romagna.
“The number of units in Italy has increased irrationally,” says Paolo Protti, president of Anec. “It’s okay to build new facilities, but you should also ensure the survival of those that already exist, because when an urban cinema closes, not all of its entrants are willing to go through the multiplexes.
Not to mention the unfilled funds intended to support the operators: the overdue debt of the State is estimated at around EUR 10 million.
From an ethical and moral point of view, it is shameful that the government does not comply with the legislation in force.
We would need 16 to 18 million euros a year to maintain the market.”
The case of Bologna deserves special attention. It is the first Italian city that, in its concern over the closures, decided to remedy the problem through an agreement between the municipality and Anec in order to protect and boost the one-room cinemas in the outer and inner city.
The provisions would include tax incentives for operators and benefits for the public to facilitate accessibility: viewers would be able to enter restricted zones and park in certain parking areas at reduced rates.
“I like this initiative,” says Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities, even with other measures, will follow Bologna’s example.
But it’s also certain that traditional cinemas, in order to be able to fight back against the domination of multiplexes, have to improve the sound and image quality, because today’s audiences are much more demanding.
The preservation of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of Supercinema in Bagheria, where I spent my childhood and adolescence, gave me the spark that made me finally make Cinema Paradiso, even though I had been thinking about it for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, so when I go to the Via Nazionale to see the closed Rialto or the Quirinale, so as not to see the blackened posters, I turn my head away.
