The energy comes from the waves, and now comes the big ones
An inexhaustible source of energy that makes up 70 percent of the planet’s surface and is still being discovered by major international energy companies.
Waves, ocean currents, tides, are all a renewable source of energy that giants like Chevron, who are now trying to get their hands on.
In the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, research intensified into the possibility of extracting energy from the sea.
Around 1980, when the price of oil fell, the idea of using marine energy was discarded, but today the demands of environmental protection and the renewed rise in oil prices give new impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity demand could be met by offshore installations.
This is twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be currents and tides.
The giants are moving.
Enersis was the first company to commit to offshore energy and in 2005 signed an agreement to build a power plant in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolutionary move when the signing was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies are opting for marine energy, including some who have been committed supporters of conventional energy.
“Chevron is studying technologies that harness the energy of the oceans and is considering working with us,” a spokesman for the U.S. oil giant’s associate firm, the Wall Street Journal, said in a statement.
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a licence issued by the US Energy Commission for the launch of a project in Alaska for the exploitation of marine energy.
The matter is not insignificant, especially when you consider that the United States is currently extracting oil in Alaska, and President Bush has recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the New York-based Verdant Power Inc. and the New Jersey-based Ocean Power are on the road to extracting energy from the sea. The amount invested so far, as far as the details are known, shows a growing interest.
The technology is waiting to be developed.
According to experts, this is still a rudimentary technology, not least because the energy from the sea does not dispel doubts about its environmental impact.
Existing facilities such as those in Portugal or Scotland are all small and therefore do not pose a major problem for the ecosystem.
However, in order to produce energy on a larger scale, we need facilities with a greater environmental impact.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses an interconnected buoy system.
The shocks generated by the waves and moving the buoys up and down are converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders placed in them.
The pressure rotates a turbine, which in turn feeds a generator.
The electricity is transmitted to the land by cables under the sea.
At the moment, there are four similar facilities at the planning stage, which are only waiting for federal approval. Some of the energy produced would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started generating energy for a shopping mall and a parking lot with six submarine turbines in the East River Strait of New York.
At tide, the movement of the water rotates the blades of the turbines, and this rotational movement feeds the generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of partners who are only waiting for permits to use energy.
Waves followed by tides.
At present, the opportunities to be exploited through the tidal wave deserve special attention.
Although it is a periodic phenomenon, tidal activity is more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and can therefore be considered a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine, Alaska, and other coastal states spent $7.5 million in 2008 to harness the energy of the tides, which is expected to rise to $35 million in 2009.
